 alt="lickthestranger" src="http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/493885523d5d628fff89c204f5a9ef79?s=30&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG" class="avatar avatar-30"></img>\n                          </a>\n                        </li>\n                        <li>\n                          <a rel="nofollow" title="galaxybureau" href="http://gravatar.com/galaxybureau" class="wpl-liker" shape="rect">\n                            <img height="30" width="30" alt="galaxybureau" src="http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/8e76f79c50e4db73d43287b87cfcb314?s=30&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG" class="avatar avatar-30"></img>\n                          </a>\n                        </li>\n                      </ul>\n                    </div>\n                  </div>\n                </div>\n              </div>\n              <footer class="entry-meta">\n                <p class="cat-links taxonomy-links">\n                  Posted in\n                  <a rel="category tag" title="View all posts in Survivors" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/category/terry-nation/survivors/" shape="rect">Survivors</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="category tag" title="View all posts in Terry Nation" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/category/terry-nation/" shape="rect">Terry Nation</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="category tag" title="View all posts in TV Reviews" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/category/tv-reviews/" shape="rect">TV Reviews</a>\n                </p>\n                <p class="tag-links taxonomy-links">\n                  Tagged\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/arts/" shape="rect">Arts</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/bbc/" shape="rect">BBC</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/bbc-america/" shape="rect">BBC America</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/colony/" shape="rect">Colony</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/outcasts/" shape="rect">Outcasts</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/post-apocalyptic/" shape="rect">Post-Apocalyptic</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/sci-fi/" shape="rect">sci-fi</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/science-fiction/" shape="rect">science fiction</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/survivor/" shape="rect">Survivor</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/survivors/" shape="rect">Survivors</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/television/" shape="rect">Television</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/television-program/" shape="rect">Television program</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/tom/" shape="rect">Tom</a>\n                  ,\n                  <a rel="tag" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/tag/united-states/" shape="rect">United States</a>\n                </p>\n                <p class="date-link">\n                  <a rel="bookmark" title="Permalink to Survivors (2008) Episode\xc2\xa03" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/05/09/survivors-2008-episode-3/" class="permalink" shape="rect">\n                    <span class="month">May</span>\n                    <span class="sep">\xc2\xb7</span>\n                    <span class="day">09</span>\n                  </a>\n                </p>\n              </footer>\n</article>\n            <article \n            class="post-708 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-misc-reviews category-tv-reviews category-uncategorized tag-a-for-andromeda tag-andromeda tag-andromeda-galaxy tag-bbc tag-doctor-who-2 tag-lost-in-time tag-remake tag-television tag-tom-hardy tag-united-states has-featured-image" id="post-708">\n              <div class="entry-image">\n                <a rel="bookmark" title="Permalink to A for Andromeda\xc2\xa0(2006)" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/04/14/a-for-andromeda-2006/" shape="rect">\n                  <img alt="" src="http://spdk1.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/a-for_andromeda_2006.jpg" class="featured-image"></img>\n                </a>\n              </div>\n              <header class="entry-header">\n                <h1 class="entry-title">\n                  <a rel="bookmark" title="Permalink to A for Andromeda\xc2\xa0(2006)" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/04/14/a-for-andromeda-2006/" shape="rect">A for Andromeda\xc2\xa0(2006)</a>\n                </h1>\n                <div class="entry-meta">\n                  <span class="byline">\n                    Posted by\n                    <span class="author vcard">\n                      <a rel="author" title="View all posts by spdk1" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/author/spdk1/" class="url fn n" shape="rect">spdk1</a>\n                    </span>\n                  </span>\n                  <span class="sep"> \xe2\x80\x94 </span>\n                  <span class="entry-date">\n                    <time pubdate="pubdate" datetime="2012-04-14T02:46:54+00:00">April 14, 2012</time>\n                  </span>\n                </div>\n                <p class="comments-link">\n                  <a title="Comment on A for Andromeda\xc2\xa0(2006)" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/04/14/a-for-andromeda-2006/#comments" shape="rect">2</a>\n                </p>\n              </header>\n              <div class="entry-content">\n                <p>\n                  I first heard about\n                  <em>A for Andromeda</em>\n                  in an unlikely, although not surprising, place. I had never heard of the original 1961 television series for two reasons, first, one can blame the fact that I am American and was born in 1982, secondly, one can look to the loss of most of the original program via the old\n                  <a target="_blank" rel="wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BBC" title="BBC" class="zem_slink" shape="rect">BBC</a>\n                  \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93who gives a crap\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd archival policy on filmed material. This was the very same policy that destroyed countless old\n                  <em>\n                    <a target="_blank" rel="wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Who" title="Doctor Who" class="zem_slink" shape="rect">Doctor Who</a>\n                  </em>\n                  episodes and many other historically important shows. There was a Documentary on a DVD set called\n                  <em>\n                    <a target="_blank" rel="wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_in_Time_%28Doctor_Who%29" title="Lost in Time (Doctor Who)" class="zem_slink" shape="rect">Lost in Time</a>\n                  </em>\n                  , in which orphaned\n                  <em>Doctor Who</em>\n                  episodes were pulled together so that they could be released in some way. This documentary filled me in on this \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93junking\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd situation and mentioned more things lost forever, including a show called\n                  <em>A for Andromeda</em>\n                  , touted as being one of the first BBC science fiction programs. I must have gone to Wikipedia or some such, as I had quickly discovered that a remake was out there\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\xa0.and here we are.\n                </p>\n                <p>\n                  <a href="http://spdk1.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/a-for_andromeda_tom_hardy_2.jpg" shape="rect">\n                    <img alt="" src="http://spdk1.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/a-for_andromeda_tom_hardy_2.jpg?w=440" title="A-For_Andromeda_Tom_Hardy_2" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-709"></img>\n                  </a>\n                </p>\n                <p>\n                  The serial opens with a \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93zooming in on the earth\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd shot eerily similar to the one from\n                  <em>Rose</em>\n                  , a 2005 episode of the resurrected\n                  <em>Doctor Who</em>\n                  . This shot was re-used on that show, and its spinoffs, countless times in the last few years; this really makes me wonder if the BBC had to keep using it for some reason. Like maybe the BBC spent a ton of money for it and needed to make ends meet by using it hundreds of times? Maybe a test group rated it the best part of the program so that drove its implementation on every show? I think it\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2ll be one of the great mysteries of our time.\n                </p>\n                <p>\n                  Much like 2005\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s\n                  <em>Quatermass Experiment</em>\n                  (which I need to review as well),\n                  <em>A for Andromeda</em>\n                  has an inexpensive look and feel, and yet stays away from a \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93cheap\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd appearance. Shows like\n                  <em>Hyperdrive</em>\n                  go the opposite route and try to look \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93BIG!\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd on a budget, and end up looking incredibly dated and cheap in the process. The use of \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93shaky cams\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd and small sets gives it a far less cinematic vibe than Doctor Who, but makes each scene interesting. In many cases the camera is right in the middle of dialog, as if you are somehow part of a conversation taking place. This makes the production remind me of an independent film, and makes it more charming in many ways. If you\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2re one of those people reading this and asking \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93why should I watch a six-year-old TV special that looks like an indie film?\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd there might be something of interest here. The main character, John Fleming, is played by none other than a pre-muscular\n                  <a target="_blank" rel="wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Hardy" title="Tom Hardy" class="zem_slink" shape="rect">Tom Hardy</a>\n                  . It\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s almost comical seeing him play a scrawny scientist considering his \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93tough guy\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd roles he has been getting lately. This show really proves that he is a very versatile actor, and could easily become a superstar in the future.\n                </p>\n                <p>\n                  <a href="http://spdk1.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/a-for_andromeda_tom_hardy.jpg" shape="rect">\n                    <img height="234" width="440" alt="" src="http://spdk1.files.wordpress.com/2012/04/a-for_andromeda_tom_hardy.jpg?w=440&amp;h=234" title="A-For_Andromeda_Tom_Hardy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-710"></img>\n                  </a>\n                </p>\n                <p>\n                  The story of\n                  <em>A for Andromeda</em>\n                  follows a group of scientists that discover a microwave signal coming from the\n                  <a target="_blank" rel="wikipedia" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andromeda_Galaxy" title="Andromeda Galaxy" class="zem_slink" shape="rect">Andromeda Galaxy</a>\n                  . Once decoded, this signal is turned into a computer program that could be a huge breakthrough for all mankind \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x80\x9c or be its undoing. The plot is a fairly hard science fiction (as in scientifically sound) story without all the bells and whistles that decorate many modern productions. Most British science fiction relies on concepts and dialog rather than sheer spectacle, and I believe this very program is a good case for this distinction between British sci-fi and US sci-fi. While this story is one of the productions biggest strengths, it is also a huge fault in the grand scheme of things.\n                </p>\n                <p>\n                  Hard sci-fi relies on realistic takes on the genre, so one would imagine dialog and concepts that show great care in \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93keeping it real\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd. Instead we get material in a similar vein to all those procedural crime dramas on U.S. TV. A scientist pounds on the keyboard, says some technobabble, and *boom* something amazing happens that is truly unrealistic to modern science. It is in this way that while\n                  <em>A for Andromeda</em>\n                  tries to be \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93hard sci-fi\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xef\xbf\xbd it\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s really more of a drama \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x80\x9c Like sci-fi for the CSI crowd.\n                </p>\n                <p>\n                  I really liked this show despite its over-simplification of things, and it\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s resemblance to a type of TV that I really do not enjoy. The acting is great, the direction is good considering the budget, and the actors involved all do a great job. For me, the highlight really was seeing Tom Hardy playing something different from a gangster or assassin, and fans of his should really check this out.\n                </p>\n                <div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled sd-sharing-enabled">\n                  <div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled">\n                    <div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-icon sd-sharing">\n                      <h3 class="sd-title">Share this:</h3>\n                      <div class="sd-content">\n                        <ul>\n                          <li class="share-google-plus-1">\n                            <div class="googleplus1_button">\n                              <div data-href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/04/14/a-for-andromeda-2006/" data-callback="sharing_plusone" data-size="medium" class="g-plusone"></div>\n                            </div>\n                          </li>\n                          <li class="share-tumblr">\n                            <a title="Click to share on Tumblr" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/04/14/a-for-andromeda-2006/?share=tumblr" rel="nofollow" class="share-tumblr sd-button share-icon no-text" shape="rect">\n                              <span></span>\n                            </a>\n                          </li>\n                          <li class="share-facebook">\n                            <a title="Share on Facebook" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/04/14/a-for-andromeda-2006/?share=facebook" rel="nofollow" id="sharing-facebook-708" class="share-facebook sd-button share-icon no-text" shape="rect">\n                              <span></span>\n                            </a>\n                          </li>\n                          <li class="share-linkedin">\n                            <a title="Click to share on LinkedIn" href="http://anamericanviewofbritishsciencefiction.com/2012/04/14/a-for-andromeda-2006/?share=linkedin